### Collision between two masses with the same mass

Suppose that two bodies with the same mass \(m\) collide elastically and the body on the right has an initial velocity of zero,

By the Principle of Conservation of Linear Momentum (taking rightward as positive),

\[mu_{1}=m\nu_{1}+m\nu_{2}\]

Since the collision is elastic, kinetic energy is also conserved.

Relative speed of Approach = Relative speed of Separation

\[u_{1}=\nu_{2}-\nu_{1}\]

Subtracting equation (2) from equation (1),

\[2\nu_{1}=0\]

Therefore,

\[\nu_{1}=0\]

Sub \(\nu_{1}=0\) into equation (1) or (2),

\[\nu_{2}=u_{1}\]

This implies that the mass which was initially moving will come to a stop after collision and the mass that was initially stationary will move off with the same velocity as the mass that was initially moving. In other words, there is a complete transfer of kinetic energy.

